:::summary
The history of the United States is one of the most consequential national narratives in the modern world — a story that begins with classical ideals and Christian convictions embedded in the founding generation, traces the expansion of a republic across a continent, confronts the great moral contradiction of slavery through a devastating civil war, and projects American power and influence into the global arena of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. To understand American history is to understand the long conversation between its classical republican inheritance, its Christian moral foundations, and the ongoing struggle to live up to its own declared ideals.
